 welfare state to neoliberalism, which have shifted the politics of redistribution from contested political arenas to design practices operating within market logics, ultimately relocating political struggles onto the city’s most intimate crevices. In so doing, she raises critical questions about the role of market reforms in redistributing resources and challenges readers to rethink neoliberalism and the fundamental ways it shapes cities and polities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzEgyptzCairo. 0aCity planningzTurkeyzIstanbul. 0aLand use, UrbanzEgyptzCairo. 0aLand use, UrbanzTurkeyzIstanbul. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027386?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027386/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles